Movies EDA¶

Introduction¶

We will explore a large data set movies and see if we can answer these questions:

  • Are more movies being released in recent years?
  • Are certain genres more popular throughout the years?
  • Does runtime depend on the genre of the movie?
  • Is there a link between runtime and quality of the movie?
  • Is there a link between movie genres and poster color intensity?
  • .. and at the end: an idea for trying to predict movie genre based on most common words in its overview/subtitles.

The Data¶

The data we are going to use is the following set from kaggle.com:

  • 350 000+ movies from themoviedb.org provided by Stephanerappeneau (Last updated in 2017)

We are going to extract that archive in data/350000_movies_dataset.

In [3]:
movie_details = pd.read_csv("data/350000_movies_dataset/AllMoviesDetailsCleaned.csv", sep = ";", thousands = ",", 
                            encoding = "utf-8-sig", index_col = [0], parse_dates = ["release_date"], low_memory = False)

The Cleaning¶

First of all, let's remove the columns which we won't need.

In [4]:
movie_details_cleaned = movie_details.drop(["original_title", "original_language", "spoken_languages_number", 
                                            "tagline", "production_companies", "production_companies_number",
                                            "budget", "revenue"], axis = 1)

Movies with no titles might be just missing data. We will discard those.

Let's also rename some columns and fix column types. Pandas supports a nullable int type so we will use that for the runtime.

In [5]:
movie_details_cleaned = movie_details_cleaned[~movie_details_cleaned.title.isnull()]

# After looking through 'production_countries' it only ever contains only one country? 
movie_details_cleaned = movie_details_cleaned.rename(columns = {"production_countries": "country"})
movie_details_cleaned = movie_details_cleaned.drop("production_countries_number", axis = 1, errors = "ignore")
# .. same with "spoken_languages"
movie_details_cleaned = movie_details_cleaned.rename(columns = {"spoken_languages": "language"})

movie_details_cleaned.runtime = movie_details_cleaned.runtime.astype(float).replace(0, float("NaN")).astype("Int64")

The language and country columns contain values that signify missing data. Let's convert all of them to np.nan:

In [6]:
def clean_values_from_columns(data, cols, values, replace = np.nan):
    """
    `data` - the data set
    `cols` - a list of the the names of the columns as a string
    `values` - a list of values which should be cleaned
    `replace` - the value which replaces them (by default nan)
    """
    for value in values:
        for col in cols:
            data[col] = data[col].replace(value, replace)
In [7]:
clean_values_from_columns(movie_details_cleaned, ["language"], ["?????", "??????", "No Language", "none"])
clean_values_from_columns(movie_details_cleaned, ["country"], ["none"])

The final columns are the following:

  • release_date
  • status - Released, In Production, Post Production, Planned, Rumored, Canceled
  • title - translated in English for foreign movies
  • overview - a short text describing the movie
  • genres - a list separated by "|"
  • country - the country in which the movie was produced
  • language - the language that is spoken in the movie
  • runtime - in minutes
  • popularity - relative popularity of the movie (at the time of gathering the information I guess). This number is from themoviedb.org
  • vote_average - the average rating (0 - 10)
  • vote_count - number of people who have given a rating
  • imdb_id - the id of the movie in https://www.imdb.com/ (we will later join that with another data set)

Different characteristics over the years¶

Number of movies per year¶

Let's take the movies which have been released and plot them by year.

In [17]:
movies_released = movie_details[movie_details.status == "Released"]
movies_released = movies_released.drop("status", axis = 1) 
movies_released = movies_released[~movies_released.release_date.isnull()]
In [18]:
number_of_movies_by_year = movies_released.groupby(movies_released.release_date.dt.year).count().release_date

plt.plot(number_of_movies_by_year.index, number_of_movies_by_year)
plt.title("Number of movies released in the years 1870-2017")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Number of movies")
plt.show()

Our data suggests that movies are getting more and more popular.

But we can also see that there is a big dip after around 2017. That's probably not because people suddenly stopped making movies.\ There are a few explanations:

  1. Our dataset was actually taken in 2017. So that explains a big chunk of missing information for the recent years.
  2. Not all movies have been released. Some are in production/post production or planned.

Let's see all records of movies before 1890:

These are some of the first films ever. They were only 1-2 minutes long and had a very basic concept (e.g. "Human Figure in Motion").

Of course as technology advanced and more capabilities were available, the medium gained popularity, leading to the spike of movies being made after the 2000s.

If seems though as the curve grows too quickly. Maybe our dataset is biased towards recent movies?

This article reaches a conclusion that way more movies are being made in recent years. But not as much. According to it the growth is around twice as much movies released in 2016 compared to 2000. That is significantly less than what our plot shows.

Going forward we should keep in mind that release date is most likely biased towards recent years.

Genre popularity¶

Are certain genres more popular throughout the years?

First we must figure out the unique genres contained in the dataset. Which is way more complicated than movies_released.genres.unique(). The entries in the dataset contain multiple genres as a string separated by |.

In [20]:
# Get the movies which don't have missing genres
movie_details_genres = movies_released[~movies_released.genres.isnull()]
In [21]:
unique_genres = set()
for index, genres in movie_details_genres.genres.str.split("|").items():
    for genre in genres:
        if genre == "": continue
        unique_genres.add(genre)
print(unique_genres)

Now we split the dataset into multiple smaller ones based on genre and save them in a dict.\ We also take movies after the year 1900 since there too few movies per year before that.

If you run it (I've commented it out on purpose to reduce clutter) you can see it's a very horrible. It's hard to see the differences between genres and doesn't really show the popularity (just the number of movies, and that follows the same curve we saw earlier - way more movies in each genre in the recent years because of way more movies in general and the bias in our data).

We can do better. Instead, for a given genre, we will calculate the percentage of all movies released that year which were in that genre. We also arrange the plots side by side for a more compact view.

In [24]:
def plot_by_genre_side_by_side(title, plot_func):
    """
    `title` - the title of the entire figure
    `plot_func` - called for each funtion, must take parameters (genre, ax)
    """
    ncols = 4
    nrows = math.ceil(len(unique_genres) / 4)

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows = nrows, ncols = ncols, figsize = (14, 9))
    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize = 18, y = 1.025)
    
    row, col = 0, 0
    for genre in unique_genres:
        ax = axes[row, col]
        ax.set_title(str(genre))
        
        plot_func(genre, ax)
    
        col += 1
        if col == ncols:
            row += 1
            col = 0
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In [25]:
percentages = dict()

for genre in unique_genres:
    genre_data = movie_details_grouped_by_genre[genre]
    percentage = genre_data.groupby(genre_data.release_date.dt.year).count().release_date
    percentages[genre] = percentage / number_of_movies_by_year
In [26]:
def genre_popularity_plotter(genre, ax):
    p = percentages[genre]
    ax.plot(p.index, p)   
    
    ax.set_ylim(0, 0.4) # Make the scale between 0 and 100 percent
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mtick.PercentFormatter(1.0))
    ax.set_xlim(1900, 2017)
    
plot_by_genre_side_by_side("Popularity (% of all movies released) of each genre by year from 1900 to 2017", genre_popularity_plotter)

There a couple of interesting things we can see:

  • First of all, the most popular genres overall seem to be drama and comedy.
  • Western movies were popular before the 1980s, but never again.
  • War movies spiked in popularity around WWII.
  • Fantasy was very popular in the 00s but since we have too few records of movies from that time it's probably just an anomaly from having a small sample.

Differences in runtime by genre¶

Does runtime depend on the genre of the movie?

We made our plot_by_genre_side_by_side function general. So let's plot histograms of movie runtimes by genre.

Also, let's plot them with density = True. This "normalizes" the histograms so they don't depend on the number of inputs of a given genre - earlier we saw there are a lot more comedy/drama movies than anything else for example. This gives us a better picture on the distributions.

In [28]:
runtimes = dict()
for genre in unique_genres:
    genre_data = movie_details_grouped_by_genre[genre]
    runtimes[genre] = genre_data[~genre_data.runtime.isnull()].runtime
In [29]:
def genre_runtimes_plotter(genre, ax):
    ax.hist(runtimes[genre], bins = "fd", density = True)   
    
    ax.set_xlim(0, 300) # We know our data set doesn't contain movies longer than 300 minutes.
    ax.set_ylim(0, 0.065) # Make the plots have the same y-scale, this was chosen by first looking at all plots...
    
plot_by_genre_side_by_side("Runtimes (in min) by genre, plotted as density", genre_runtimes_plotter)

We see that most of the plots look similar and look like normal distrubutions. All of them have outliers which are either outside the plot (in the positive x direction) or between 0-40 minutes of runtime - except for the animation genre. In that case things are very different.. most animations are shorter than 50 minutes.

This leads to the question. Are there significant differences between the runtimes of different genres?

We will first run a one-way ANOVA test and then a t-test on each pair of genres and visualize all p-values with a matrix.

Let's go all in and test that for each combination of genres. Formulating our pair of hypothesis:

  • $H_0:$ Genre runtimes are samples from the same distribution. Nothing interesting.
  • $H_1:$ There are significant differences between genre runtimes.

We can't use the runtimes dict directly and we need to do some work on the data first - .. because movies can have multiple genres and in movie_details_grouped_by_genre samples can overlap. To solve this problem we will take the first genre in the movie genre list and consider it as "main" and the rest as less important sub-genres. The genres are not ordered alphabetically so we assume the first one is the most important.

In [30]:
movie_details_grouped_by_main_genre = dict()
for genre in unique_genres:
    movie_details_grouped_by_main_genre[genre] = movie_details_genres[(movie_details_genres.genres.str.startswith(genre)) 
                                                                  & (movie_details_genres.release_date.dt.year > 1900)]
In [31]:
non_overlapping_runtimes = dict()
for genre in unique_genres:
    genre_data = movie_details_grouped_by_main_genre[genre]
    non_overlapping_runtimes[genre] = genre_data[~genre_data.runtime.isnull()].runtime

Since our data set is very large, let's use a confidence level of $ \alpha_{c} = 0.1\% $.

In [32]:
alpha = 0.001
In [33]:
anova_pvalue = stats.f_oneway(*non_overlapping_runtimes.values()).pvalue
print(f"Running ANOVA resulted in a pvalue of {anova_pvalue}.")
if anova_pvalue < alpha:
    print("Null-hypothesis is probably false.")
else:
    print("Null-hypothesis can't be rejected with this confidence level.")

Running ANOVA resulted in a pvalue of 0.0.
Null-hypothesis is probably false.

ANOVA can’t tell us which specific groups were statistically significantly different from each other, only that at least two of the groups were.

Let's go all in and run t-test for each combination of genres. Formulating our hypothesis for each pair of genres:

  • $H_0:$ genre_1's runtimes is not not correlated with genre_2's runtime.
  • $H_1:$ genre_1's runtimes and genre_2's runtimes come from two significantly different distributions.

To visualize all p-values we will use a matrix:

In [34]:
genres = list(unique_genres)

pvalue_matrix = pd.DataFrame(index = genres, columns = genres)
idx = pvalue_matrix.columns.union(pvalue_matrix.index)
pvalue_matrix = pvalue_matrix.reindex(index = list(idx)[:-1], columns = list(reversed(idx))[:-1], fill_value = 0)

Now we perform a t-test for each pair of genres with our $\alpha_{c} = 0.1\%$:

In [35]:
for i in range(len(genres)):
    for j in range(i + 1, len(genres)):
        g1, g2 = genres[i], genres[j]
        r1, r2 = runtimes[g1], runtimes[g2]
        pvalue_matrix.loc[g1, g2] = stats.ttest_ind(r1, r2, equal_var = False).pvalue

Color all values less than alpha critical green.

def color_green_or_gray(value):
    if np.isnan(value): return ("color: white; background-color: white")
    
    color = "green" if value < alpha else "gray"
    return "color: %s" % color
pvalue_matrix.style.applymap(color_green_or_gray).format("{:g}")

First of all, we will take movies with at least 100 ratings (arbitrarily chosen).\ This discards movies with little vote counts and thus a garbage vote_average.

Correlation between release year and rating¶

I'm sure you've heard people say older movies are better.. modern blockbusters are just cash-grabs.. directors stopped caring about art..

There are interesting articles and even some discussion happening in the comments: Are Movies Getting Worse?\ Why Dustin Hoffman Thinks Movies Are Getting Worse

The first one even has a plot of how the opinion of critics and citizens is vastly different about modern movies.

Let's leave all that to the side and see what our data tells us:

In [45]:

plt.xlabel("Year released")
plt.ylabel("Rating")
plt.ylim(0, 10)
plt.legend(loc = "lower left")
plt.show()

There is definitely some correlation. Although our data set is biased - there are way more recent movies in it and thus way more worse recent movies.\ Also young people are more likely to watch modern movies and give ratings (we chose movies with above 100 ratings, but older people don't cope well with technology and don't bother with ratings on web sites...)

All in all, the difference in there - but we can't say for sure it is as big as the plot suggests.

Movie posters color intensity¶

Is there a link between movie genres and poster color intensity?

The data we are going to use is the following set from kaggle.com:

  • Poster Image Dataset of Hollywood Movies provided by Pranav Hari (Last updated in 2020)

We are going to extract that archive in data/poster_downloads.

! Note: ! This data set is large in size (about 8000 images, 116 MB). I provided a much smaller version but you can download the full one.

For each image we calculate the average intensity of each channel and then the overall intesity.\ In the end posters_rgb_intensities contains tuples of the format (movie_info, [r, g, b, total])).

In [55]:
posters_rgb_intensities = list()

# Make sample_size None to read all posters in the folder instead of an explicit sample size.
sample_size = None

# Reads a sample of the posters in the data set
for filename in os.listdir("data/poster_downloads"):
    imdb_id = filename.split("_")[1][:-4]
    
    # Checks if there is a movie with that given imdb_id, if not we don't read the image
    mask = movie_details_genres.imdb_id == imdb_id
    if np.any(mask):
        image = skimage.io.imread("data/poster_downloads/" + filename)
        info = movie_details_genres[mask].to_dict(orient = "list")
        
        # If the format for the image is not RGB we skip it 
        if len(image.shape) != 3: continue
        if image.shape[2] != 3: continue
            
        
        # Calculate the sum of the r, g and b channels
        r, g, b = image[:, :, 0], image[:, :, 1], image[:, :, 2]

        # Here we calculate the average intensity of each channel, and overall
        # Gamma correction is not really an issue because we compare relatively to other posters later
        r_intensity, g_intensity, b_intensity = r.mean(), g.mean(), b.mean() 

        gray_scale = image.mean(axis = 2).round().astype(np.uint8)
        intensity = gray_scale.mean()
        
        posters_rgb_intensities.append((info, [r_intensity, g_intensity, b_intensity, intensity]))
    
    if sample_size is not None:
        if sample_size == 0:
            break
        sample_size -= 1
In [56]:
def get_all_channels_per_genre(grouped, channel):
    """
    `grouped` - a dict mapping genres to lists of arrays of pre-calculated r, g, b, overall intensities
    `channel` - which channel to extract (index 0-4 where 4 is overall intensity)
    """
    result = dict()
    for genre, movies in grouped.items():
        result[genre] = []
        for movie in movies:
            result[genre].append(movie[1][channel])
    return result

def run_anova_on_channel(grouped, channel, alpha):
    """
    Uses _get_all_channels_per_genre_ to retrieve the calculated channel information.
    `grouped` - a dict mapping genres to lists of arrays of pre-calculated r, g, b, overall intensities
    `channel` - is one of: r, g, b, overall_intensity
    `alpha` - test critical value
    """
    channel_index = 0
    if channel == "r": pass
    elif channel == "g": channel_index = 1
    elif channel == "b": channel_index = 2
    elif channel == "overall_intensity": channel_index = 3
    else: raise ValueError
    
    anova_pvalue = stats.f_oneway(*get_all_channels_per_genre(grouped, channel_index).values()).pvalue
    print(f"Running ANOVA on channel \"{channel}\" of images resulted in a pvalue of {anova_pvalue}.")
    if anova_pvalue < alpha:
        print("Null-hypothesis is probably false.")
    else:
        print(f"Null-hypothesis can't be rejected with confidence level of {alpha}.")

Now we group posters to see see if there is significant difference in intensities between genres:

In [57]:
posters_grouped_by_genre = dict()

for image in posters_rgb_intensities:
    info = image[0]
    
    # Take just the first genre.
    # We called it "main" genre, they are not ordered alphabetically so we assume the first one is the most important.
    genre = info["genres"][0].split("|")[0]
    if genre == "": continue
    posters_grouped_by_genre[genre] = posters_grouped_by_genre.get(genre, []) + [image]

Run anova on each channel with the mean values we calculated earlier.

The test runs on groups (determined by genre) which contain the average intensity of a channel for each poster corresponding to a movie in that genre.

The hypothesis which we are going to test:

  • $H_0:$ Average intensities of channels are from the same distribution. Nothing interesting.
  • $H_1:$ There are significant differences between intensities of certain colors in movie posters.
In [58]:
alpha = 0.01
run_anova_on_channel(posters_grouped_by_genre, "r", alpha)

Running ANOVA on channel "r" of images resulted in a pvalue of 8.761208322425462e-43.
Null-hypothesis is probably false.
In [59]:
run_anova_on_channel(posters_grouped_by_genre, "g", alpha)

Running ANOVA on channel "g" of images resulted in a pvalue of 8.468345429608294e-45.
Null-hypothesis is probably false.
In [60]:
run_anova_on_channel(posters_grouped_by_genre, "b", alpha)

Running ANOVA on channel "b" of images resulted in a pvalue of 4.037597152134077e-37.
Null-hypothesis is probably false.
In [61]:
run_anova_on_channel(posters_grouped_by_genre, "overall_intensity", alpha)

Running ANOVA on channel "overall_intensity" of images resulted in a pvalue of 1.2874771542612296e-46.
Null-hypothesis is probably false.

! Note: ! Running on all 8000 posters results in all p-values being less than 1e-100. If we run on a smaller sample we will get bigger p-values.

Stemming vs lemmatizing?

  • "The goal of both stemming and lemmatization is to reduce inflectional forms and sometimes derivationally related forms of a word to a common base form.\ However, the two words differ in their flavor. Stemming usually refers to a crude heuristic process that chops off the ends of words in the hope of achieving this goal correctly most of the time, and often includes the removal of derivational affixes. Lemmatization usually refers to doing things properly with the use of a vocabulary and morphological analysis of words, normally aiming to remove inflectional endings only and to return the base or dictionary form of a word, which is known as the lemma."
    • Cited from: https://nlp.stanford.edu/IR-book/html/htmledition/stemming-and-lemmatization-1.html
In [66]:
documents = list()
y = list() # This is an array saying the value of the target feature of each document (used for training)

stemmer = WordNetLemmatizer()
for genre, movies in genre_samples.items():
    for overview in movies.overview.values:
        # Clean puncuation and lemmatize words 
        stripped = overview.lower().translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
        stripped = [stemmer.lemmatize(word) for word in stripped.split()]
        
        documents.append(' '.join(stripped))
    y += [hash(genre)] * len(movies)

Use TF-IDF (term frequency–inverse document frequency) to reflect importancy of words:

In [67]:
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_features = 1500, min_df = 5, max_df = 0.7, stop_words = "english")
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(documents)
